<Review ID>0942374
<Product Name>Zune 30 GB Digital Media Player (White)
<Title>Great hardware, software needs a little work
<Date>Mon Dec 24 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>After much harassment by my family, I broke down and bought the 30 GB Zune (early Christmas present to me).  I didn't want an iPOD (being somewhat a non-conformist), so the Zune works well  I must say, except for the software, it has been an excellent experience.  The 30GB Zune holds my entire MP3 library as well as all my ripped CDs I own (300+) and still only used up 15 of the 30 GB.  I have 5 full DVD movies (converted to WMV with 3rd party software) and still have over 5 GB of space left!  The storage is bloody awesome.  Now, on to the meat of it...  The Zune is very easy to navigate, the menu options are clear and concise.  I can access my songs by title, artist, and genre, but usually I just hit shuffle.  Video is the same, although I have found that playing video uses up markedly more battery life than music or the FM tuner.  The FM tuner is great - my stations all come in clear with little static, which is great for a device with no visible antenna.    The specs say up to 20 hours of continuous playing, although I have found this to be on the optimistic side.  Probably more like 12 - 15 hours, depending on how many videos you play, and how long you leave the backlight on.  The backlight can be adjusted to various timeframes (mine is set to 15 seconds), and it will definitely save you battery life if you set it low.  Speaking of settings, the volume goes from 0 - 20, but I rarely find it necessary to go beyond 7 or 8.    Physically, the Zune seems pretty tough, though I recommend getting a clear plastic overlay (like for a Palm) for the display screen.  The housing attracts fingerprints, but is easily wiped off.  The included ear buds are really not that great, and certainly not comfortable.  I would recommend headphones or a different pair of earbuds.  The sound is fine, but after extended wearing, it starts to hurt.   Now, the software.  The Zune would have rated 5 stars imho, but for the software.  It's slow, doesn't respond well, and doesn't find everything you ask it to - even after specifying the folders where songs, videos, and pictures are located.  To it's credit, the syncing is relatively quick (with a USB 2.0 port), and it will convert videos to it's preferred format (WMV) if it's able (which is to say, sometimes).  I'm sure also the minimalist design appeals to some artsy crowd, but overall it just makes it more of a pain to try and find stuff.  The "user manual" is a joke, being only about 5 pages long, and less than helpful, other than to get you up and running.    A long-winded review, but overall, I would definitely recommend the Zune, but tell Microsoft to get some design and functionality help with Windows, err. I mean the Zune software.  Merry Christmas!  
<Overall>4

