<Review ID>0582125
<Product Name>Zune 30 GB Digital Media Player (White)
<Title>Great product, but only for certain uses.
<Date>Sun Dec 23 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>First, let me say I've used only Apple iPods to this point, namely the Mini and the Nano, and recently got the Nano Video (Thank you, Secret Santa!!). The Apple products have a better overall user experience, but they also have a few limitations, particularly in regards to video.  I use Media Center to record TV. As I am usually on the road, I never see much of what I record. Converting that material to a portable format used to be such a time consuming process: it took longer to complete then it took to watch.   When MS announced the 2.0 upgrade, it piqued my interest. One click MCE integration with a portable player! When Amazon put it on sale, picking up the Zune was a no-brainer (as was update to the new 2.0 software).   It worked! DVR-MS files could be easily synced to an affordable portable player. So now I've got Daily Show and Countdown to go! Further, with an A/V kit (also got that) they can be played back on a standard TV!  It's also a really good MP3 player. One huge advantage of the large 30GB hard drive is the ability to store high bit rate MP3's. With my Mini and now my Nano, the 4GB capacity had me converting my ripped 256 VBR MP3 files to 128 AAC files. Not so bad if you're listening on ear buds, but definitely noticeable if you're listening in the car.   And now it does podcast (audio and video) with aplomb. Very handy on long trips.  So, we've got portable PVR files, great sounding audio, and podcast. What's not to like?  Well, it's larger and heavier then the current generation of flash based players (Zune, iPod, as well as the others). Bit of a mixed blessing, as the larger screen is definitely more watchable, and the 30GB HD allows you to hold a lot of video, as well as  high bit rate MP3's. But it doesn't just drop in your pocket.   Further, being Hard Drive based, like my old Mini was, battery life suffers, like my old Mini.  MS didn't include Plays For Sure, so you can't take your unbox videos with you (you listening Amazon?)  Lastly, the Zune software is not the equal of iTunes. It's not bad, it's just not the fluid experience that is iTunes.   Conclusions?  If you use Media Center (or any other PVR software for that matter) and want to watch your Video on the Go, this is the best bet for the money.  If you listen to your audio in a car, an HD based player is a probably better bet than a flash based player, unless you have a short play list.  Other than that, you are probable going to be happier with a flash based player, Zune, iPod or whatever.   
<Overall>4

