<Review ID>2947729
<Product Name>Zune 30 GB Digital Media Player (White)
<Title>Pretty impressive, but the software needs tweaking
<Date>Fri Dec 07 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>The Zune player itself is great.  The screen is bright and easy to read, and the interface is easy to learn.  I already had the Zune software on my computer for media sharing with my Xbox 360, so my library was set up.  I was able to get the unit to sync up within a few minutes and was using my Zune in less than an hour.  The sound quality is excellent, both through the supplied headphones and output through my car stereo.  It was extremely difficult to get the little foam covers onto the headphones and they tend to slide off in use, but they aren't necessary.  Battery life in music mode is excellent if you set the screen to turn off quickly; I have mine set for five seconds.  Since the charge is handled through USB, it's easy to find a place to hook it up.  There are inexpensive USB converters for wall outlets and car lighter ports and many home electronics items have USB ports (stereos, satellite/cable boxes, game systems, etc.) that can be used.  The WiFi share function worked flawlessly the one time I used it.  When the next-generation Zune players launched in mid-November there was a major software update.  While the computer interface was greatly improved graphically, some of the functionality and options of the old software disappeared.  The main menu font on the Zune is much larger and easier to read, but all of the other text is smaller (and harder to read while driving).  The old software allowed you to right-click a track and get to the tag editor, this function was removed.  I also find that I have to disconnect and reconnect my unit to get the sync to work, which was never a problem before.  Hopefully, these items will be fixed in a future update.  Also added was the Zune card (at zune.net), an online page that lets you share your plays with others and lets them sample (and buy) tracks available through the Zune Marketplace.  Existing Xbox Live or Windows Live accounts can be used for logging in to zune.net.  In addition, the Microsoft Points used for Xbox Live downloads are also used to purchase music through the Marketplace.  I have downloaded a couple of free tracks from the Marketplace but haven't really explored the catalog.    I would like to have more control of the unit itself.  I'd like to see more fonts available and in different sizes.  I'd also like to be able to set the equalizer levels myself; there are times when all of the presets fail in one way or another.  Finally, I'd like to see a shortcut to get to the settings menu quickly (like holding down the "back" button for a couple of seconds).  There should be a way to assign a shortcut to each direction of the controller, similar to most newer cell phones.  Overall, the Zune is definitely worth the money.  I picked mine up just before the next-gen units shipped and saved $60.  Software issues kept it from getting a five-star rating.  
<Overall>4

