<Review ID>3052900
<Product Name>Zune 30 GB Digital Media Player (White)
<Title>Bought 2 for each daughter and regret it!
<Date>Sun Aug 05 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>Nothing but problems and more problems.  Customer service is a joke and so is the non-existent product line.  I don't know where to start.  Customer service is what is making me want to get rid of these expensive desk decorations as these guys don't know their heads from their back ends.    After 3 days of calling and Microsoft cancelling our account and all the hours upon hours of downloaded songs expiring and getting different "this is how you fix it" stories from many dingalings, we thought we finally got it running again.  Not so.  Microsoft couldn't reconnect my account after their shutting it down by mistake AND charging us for a month we never used, so we had to start over by opening a new account. (Our account was 7 months old and had a tremendous amount of downloaded songs... all were automatically "expired" so no using the Zune). Nothing would work on their software which kept coming up with our old accounts names and numbers (after re-signing up) and allowing anything to work.  Old "tags" stay on the screen and new ones wouldn't come up and be added or replace these so we could access the songs.  Our account showed the account as reopened but wouldn't allow us access to anything after charging our credit card TWICE to get it started again.  It goes on and on with the help of several idiots at Microsoft which so far has wasted about 6 hours of my time and still they won't work again.  All songs (we'd downloaded about 1,000 to our Zunes so they DID work for a month or two and it was almost nice) expired and we had to START EVERYTHING OVER. Like that would do any good. Obviously I'm incredibly frustrated with this as much money has been spent not only on 2 Zunes but cords, sets of new cords to replace ones that stopped working, monster cords to replace the new cords which also stopped working and a monthly $15 charge just to access songs that I can't get access to.  ARGH!  Anyway, I have had it.  The $80.00 car charging/house charging set stopped working (cheap garbage), the cords that charge and connect to the pc don't work properly (sometimes work..sometimes do nothing) and it's nothing but a pointless hassle.  Trying to find accessories was so frustrating I gave up.  Radio Shack kept telling us "buy Ipod accessories, they ALL work with Zune". Right... Best Buy carried nothing but the Zune itself...oh...and Zune gift cards which the website wouldn't accept!  We finally found ONE overpriced dock that has some sort of speaker system to project sound in their rooms. The huge price (When Ipod has loads of accessories and for 1/3 the price!) kept me from wasting my money.  The only thing that's worked for more than a few months is the "monster charger" for the car.  That is great.  But unfortunately you need a crappy ZUNE to make it worthwhile.  I hate these things and am ready to sell them on eBay for IPODS!!  HORRIBLE!  Beware before you buy as you apparently must have lots of time and $$ to waste!  
<Overall>1

<Review ID>1027558
<Product Name>Zune 30 GB Digital Media Player (White)
<Title>The Microsoft Zune
<Date>Sun Jul 22 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>Over half the reviews i have seen on this product seem to be from people who do not actually own the very product they are reviewing, they either rate it a 5 star and say anything from "It's not an ipod, thank god!" or a 1 star "Wi-Fi sucks, no plays-for-sure, get an iPod!" Where is the user experience??? Well, to kick off my review I will tell you what most people will not know without user experience.   The zune software, ITS REALLY GOOD. All the glitches you have heard have been fixed, I installed it within a matter of maybe 10 minutes, and in that 10 minutes i downloaded it, installed it, downloaded updates, set up my Zune, entered my information to download through Zune Marketplace, and started syncing my music to my zune. All within a matter of 10 minutes. Here is some cool fun facts about the software:  You know when you plug in an ipod, or just about any other mp3 player, you get the "Do Not Disconnect", or "Connected" or something along the lines. You cannot even use your mp3 player while its charging via computer USB. The unique thing about the zune software, is that if you have your Zune plugged in and the Zune Software open, the zune charges and it says "connected" on its screen, and just like any other MP3 player, you cant do anything with it. BUT, with out even touching the zune product, you just close out of the Zune Software on your computer, and Poof! Your zune is still charging and you can use it.  Zune software, similar to iTunes, automatically downloads album artwork and updates song information.  There is not much else to say about the software, its REALLY easy to use, very sleek, and runs just as smoothly.   The Zune... ahh here is where it gets good  First thing, this is kind of cool, and i dont think anyone has mentioned it. When i entered the Serial Number into the Zune website to register it. I noticed a few things: 1: the serial number is kinda dug into the zune, it isnt printed right onto the surface, its hard to describe in words, but it just makes it so that it cant easily scratch off and become illegible.   2:  There is a little message "Hello from Seattle" kind of cool... just thought ide say it.  Ok enough about that, lets talk about size (its huge right? thats what everyone says!!!)  Huge? Hah! this thing is tiny! A Dollar bill completely covers the face of it with 2 inches hanging over it, as far as thickness goes, it is exactly the thickness of 2 #2 pencils, it is really not that big, its just bigger than the ipod, so people say its HUGE or that it is a brick.   Now navigation.. (it sucks right? I mean, theres no click wheel! Its a phony!!)  Hmm... well, again, its hard to explain, but it is really, really easy to navigate through your 3000+ songs. I have a little over 2,300 songs, and i get to what i want to listen to in no time.. heres an example: Im searching through my mp3's in Artist mode, so i see all of the artists. I want to listen to "Bullet for my Valentine" but i accidentally go to Buckcherry, with the iPod, you have to press menu, then move the cursor down to Bullet for my Valentine, then press "ok", well, with the Zune, you just simple press the left side of the directional pad, again, its hard to explain, it really is, ill just give you the verdict. ITS REALLY EASY.  The Screen, (Sure, its big, but it has the same resolution!) True... but to the human eye pictures/menu/songs/movies look no different, some reviewers said that it made everything look really blurry.. thats some BS right there. You cant even tell, if Microsoft hadnt released that the resolution was the same, not a single person would have noticed.  Overall performance (IT FREAKIN LAGS, its the slowest buggiest MP3 player ever!!) Again, B to the S. The only time i have ever, EVER gotten a lag of any sort, is when I am playing a song, and at the "now playing screen" and i rapidly press "back" 5 or six times to get to the main menu, yeah, theres a lag. But to prevent that just press and hold the back button and the main menu will appear shortly.. no lag.  File support (It doesnt support Playsforsure, and only supports WMV video!! Get a freakin iPod) What i think is the most ridiculous thing ever about the zune is the fellow that says this: The zune doesnt support Microsoft's own Playsforsure format, so please, leave all your troubles behind and get an iPod!  What is so bad about that is that the iPod doesnt support Playsforsure either.. so how does getting an ipod leave all your troubles behind, if you are Napster, Yahoo, URGE, Rhapsody, any of those, they will not work with an iPod, the will not work with a Zune... I recommend the Zen Vision: M for playing "playsforsure" somgs.  The Wi-fi (it sucks, 3 days 3 plays is soo bad!!!" Thats totally true, but think of it this way, look at the PSP:  when it was first released, you could only share pictures and play ad-hoc. Well now, with a ton of firmware updates (its up to 3.3 or something now) the PSP now plays online and browses the web with an internet browser. I believe it got that internet browser in update 2.0. The zune is at 1.4 firmware wise. Give it some time!!!  Color Options (theres sOOOO many, microsoft is so desperate) Theres so many because they wont people to have their own zune, not the standard black and white, Get brown, or red, or Halo 3, or even pink!! they are ALL the same price..  Packaging (no one ever said crap about this now did they) Its really nice, its compact, they packed it in really, really thick carboard, it almost feels like a thin wood. compared to the ipods packaging this is stellar. I'm not going to destroy your experience, as opening the Zune is truly really awesome, so all i will say, is that the Zune packaging is FLIPPIN AMAZING.  Contents (again, no one ever said crap about this)  It comes with a sync cable, headphones, case, zune, CD, and a manual. Headphones: These are really comfortable, so-so sound (same as ipods), but these have a unique cord management system. Like the ipod's headphopnes, they have that thing thats slides up and connects the 2 ear pieces. But the earpieces are also magnetic, so they stick together preventing a lot of tangles and knots and messes.  Sync Cable: Its even got that same doubleshot finish the zune has, other than that, its a sync cable, nothing special Case: this is a REALLY, REALLY good free-bee case. It feels really, really soft and it is perfect size. No wiggle room at all. It clings to the zune protecting it from keys, coins or whatever else is in your pocket.  CD:  yes, it actually comes with one, unlike the ipod Manual: It's a little too simple, just 3 steps  1 install software 2 charge zune 3 load music each step showing a picture.  But they also have this product guide, that just shows all the safety precautions, like dont throw in an open flame, and ridiculous stuff like that.   Please, feel free to comment and i will answer back as soon as i can.   I HIGHLY RECOMMEND THE ZUNE TO ANYONE WHO WANTS AN MP3 PLAYER   
<Overall>5

<Review ID>3312477
<Product Name>Zune 30 GB Digital Media Player (White)
<Title>Zune and Creative Comparison w/a little iPod Mention
<Date>Mon Jul 23 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>I have read a few of the reviews here and some of the discussion board posts below. Many people compare the Zune to the iPod, and some people just talk about the Zune without giving that much helpful information. I've seen a couple people request Creative comparisons. Since I had a Creative Zen and now have a Zune, I will just write about my experiences with both, tell why I picked each player vs others, compare the two based on my experiences and give feedback on the Zune. I also want those of you who came here for a real review and not to read iPod whores talk about how the Zune doesn't stack up to the iPod, causing you maybe to get a false sense of the Zune or not know what to believe, and/or those of you who really want to know what the Zune is like to walk away from this review feeling like I've given you a real opinion that is not fanatical or anti-XYZ mp3 player in any sense on the product. I still think you should look at some of the posts by people who are so psychotic about the iPod that they troll here and/or have long, drawn-out comparisons/checklists that set out to prove how much better the iPod is than the Zune just so you can look at what features the Zune has and see which of those that are lacking and that are there matter most to you (because a lot of those things on those lists really don't matter much, at least not to me)--that's how you should make your decision (in particular, look at CFranz's review and PalmerDeville's discussion board comparison below, entitled "A Hands-On Review of the Zune (vs iPod), which I think actually has some of the Zune's alleged lack of features wrong).  (If you just want to read a review of the Zune, skip down a few paragraphs...)  And that's how I've been making my decisions about mp3 players. I got my first one, the Creative Zen Touch 20GB, almost two years ago. At the time, I was looking for what I felt was the best buy given my criteria--a player that would hold a lot of songs but was still relatively inexpensive. My school sells iPods on campus, and since I was on campus I came extremely close to rushing over to the computer store to buy a video iPod. I thought the fact that it played videos was cool, though I could live without that feature. They had a lot of GBs, so it could hold a lot of songs. Oh, and everyone had one. They were just about the only mp3 player I was hearing anything about. Two major things stopped me. First, when I realized that iPods only work with iTunes, I was turned off. I had (and still do) a subscription to Rhapsody. I love Rhapsody because the songs are great sound quality, great collection of songs and you can pay monthly, quarterly or yearly and have access to songs rather than paying per song. But with Rhapsody, you can either only stream songs all you want or you can get the subscription that allows you to transfer songs directly to your mp3 player (pretty much all players except iPods, and I think maybe even the Zunes). Basically, you license the songs--once you cancel that service, you lose the songs. I knew this when I upgraded to that service, but I did it anyway because I was lazy and didn't feel like ripping songs from all my CDs, downloading songs or using programs like Total Recorder, Limewire or (later on) Replay to get the songs I wanted for free. The second thing was the cost for the GBs, as well the cost in comparison to other players. I scanned iPods, and even with my school discount those things were either costing *over* $300 for the video iPods or cost an amount for, like, a 4GB iPod that I would have only paid for something with 10GB, at least. I've seen people say iPods cost what the Zunes do, which is something I've never witnessed...maybe iPod's prices have gone down, or certain iPods cost the same as a Zune. (Another consideration was I'd heard that there were several problems with iPods, such as breaking down, which I later learned after purchasing a Zen that they had a similar problem with many players, although mine never broke down)  This is what led me to the Creative Zen Touch 20GB. It didn't play videos or accept pictures or anything like that. It basically just played music, but it would play a LOT of it and for only $215 (where I found it). That was good enough for me, and that's what I bought. From day one, I had problems with that thing. I just thought the setup part was a little too difficult, what, with loading software onto your computer AND onto your player, then realizing there was an update and re-loading THAT software and stuff like that. The player was bulky, which was fine with me even though I noticed most other players were smaller/thinner after the fact. The look of the player, especially internally (i.e. the menus, background, etc) vs, say, the Zune reminds me of how computers from the 80s look vs computers nowadays. It was just a really plain player that, if all you wanted to do was hear a lot of music, got the job done.   But, boy, did it take a lot of work to get the job done. I noticed that Napster was offering a free trial for either a week or two weeks, so I downloaded that and started transfering songs to my Zen from their service since the Zen allegedly worked with Napster, according to Napster's compatibility list. I was considering possibly switching to Napster from Rhapsody until every time I tried to sync songs from Napster to the Zen, the sync list would get maybe 60-70% completed and then freeze up. After messing with this several times, I blamed it on Napster, cancelled after a month and then started syncing songs from Rhapsody. Rhapsody worked great with the Zen for a while, but the problem with Rhapsody is they release new versions of their program every time you turn around. Unfortunately, pretty much every time they did this I wouldn't be able to sync songs directly from Rhapsody to the Zen for a long time. Usually, once I was able to sync again without incident, Rhapsody would force another upgrade on me. Eventually, I realized Windows Media Player would sync these songs without too many problems (even though there would definitely be some problems) and started using that to sync songs after I downloaded them from Rhapsody. I also went ahead and started ripping more and more songs from my CD collection to sync, among other tricks. Those would almost never have problems syncing to Zen, unless the Zen froze up in the process...  Which brings me to more problems I experienced with the Zen. There was a period of time that, save for the problems with syncing and the occasional Zen freeze-up, I was absolutely in love with that player and swore I would never by one from any company other than Creative. Then over time, more and more problems popped up. I always felt like the Zen's advertisement of 24-hour battery life was a lie. I travel a lot, long trips, and figured theoretically that it would take 8 hours for one battery bar to go down on my player. Well...taking Amtrak to or from Ann Arbor/Chicago, basically a 5-hour trip...one bar would be down by the end of that trip. Chicago to Memphis on Amtrak, approximately 10 & 1/2 hours, two bars could be down and that's not even with me using the player the whole time. I understand that the more songs you have on the player, the lower the battery life is, but I still think it's misleading to say 24-hours. As time went by, the freezing became more frequent, and then I also started having problems with the buttons on my player making the wrong selections. I logged onto Creative's message boards a lot because I experienced so many various issues with the player, and I pretty much always found other users with the same problems, many times not even just with the Zen Touch. I was praying like hell that my player wouldn't experience any serious problems, and I never wanted to take my Zen to a repair shop for some of the more irritating problems such as the buttons not working correctly because I knew I'd probably end up losing all (eventually) 2100+ songs I put on it. Many people reformatted their Creative players or were told to, or were told to download updates/revert back to older software versions, whenever they had a problem with it, and you just lose all your songs when you do that. Another really irritating thing to deal with was how picky the player was about ID tag information for your songs. For example, if you wanted to play songs on random and you didn't have artist, title or album information entered in for a song, that song would not be included in the random shuffle. You had to edit your tags to make sure they had this information. The software to download to sync with the Zen was crap, which is why I eventually stuck with WMP above all others. I couldn't even see half the song titles on my Zen whenever tried to use that program to create playlists for my Zen. Finally, off and on, my lap top wouldn't recognize my Zen. Many times I would have to re-download the driver onto my lap top to get it to recognize it. There were other issues with the Creative Zen, areas in which they maybe could have done better (such as ease of menu navigation, etc) that customers complained about, but these were my biggest problems with that player.   ***The Zune*** (vs Zen) In my family, I'm the one everyone runs to with technology issues. But even though I had recommended Creative to several people, including my brother and sister, my brother and sister went out and bought Zunes for themselves, probably in March or April. I tried theirs out and had them tell me about their Zunes. I wasn't even really in the market for a new player, except the buttons not working right on my Zen really was getting worse and worse and more irritating, but I really liked their Zunes. I could tell that it was a better product than the Creative players, which honestly surprised me because I felt like everything Microsoft comes out with is crap and expected nothing better from their mp3 player. I liked the way it looked, and while it might not be as small as iPods it is smaller than my Zen was. I'm happy with the size. I also thought it was really cool how it played FM radio, as well as that you could see the album art while the song is playing (depending...more on this in a second).   My brother and sister always need help with any technology, so I figured they were going to have tons of questions and complaints about their Zunes--how to install/setup the Zune software, how to do this, how to do that, this or that isn't working right, etc. But the only questions I was getting from them concerned how to convert videos to WMV files. They surely would have had questions had they bought Creatives like I told them to. I see many people here claim problems with the Zune software, but they have had no such problems. I figure those problems relate to, as some have said, where your USB port is, as well as what operating system you have. My sister and brother have Windows Media Center on a computer with front USB ports, and I have Windows XP Professional Edition on a lap top with three back USB ports. They got their players working without me, got songs on their players without me and have been getting movies on their players pretty much without me.  As far as my player, I was kind of baffled at first because I didn't see an AC adapter to plug it in and charge the battery up. Then I called up my sister and found out you don't even need one with the Zune like you do with the Zen because it charges with the sync cable hooked up to your computer. Awesome. So I installed the software from the CD that came with the Zune, hooked up the Zune, honestly did have a little trouble getting the lap top to recognize the Zune but it didn't take long to fix that, and it was working. This was easier to setup than the Zen, no question, at least for me. I didn't like that the player wasn't going to work with Windows Media Player or that I'm wasting hard drive space with a program that is just like Windows Media Player (according to others here, though, it does work with WMP, but the research I did said it wouldn't. I haven't tried it with WMP), but I do like how much faster songs sync to my player with Zune's WMP copycat than WMP synced to my Zen. As far as Rhapsody, I haven't tried it with Rhapsody, although I read when I did some research on the Zune (a lot more badmouthing from iPod fanatics) that it won't work with anything but Zune's Marketplace.   At this point, that's not an issue to me anymore. And I've got to be honest with you--it's really silly to become dependent on one type of player all because you purchased their picky formats. I knew I wasn't going to have the Zen for the rest of my life, and those people with iPods who purchase songs from iTunes are not going to be able to hang onto that forever. It's a waste of money, and even my syncing songs from Rhapsody was a waste of money. I recommend thinking ahead and getting songs in formats that will be pretty universal to most players, such as mp3 and wma formats, and save all those songs on CD-Rs or DVD-Rs as data discs for when you get a new mp3 player. Those of you who get songs from iTunes know the burn-the-CD-and-rip trick--use that. I am in the process of getting my songs all license-free in mp3 and wma formats, using the songs I've ripped from CDs, as well as other ways already mentioned. Some of you might have a problem with getting music illegally, but these companies really try to tie our hands and it's ridiculous. Just a suggestion, but I know that I'm never going to have to worry about losing my songs again or how to switch mp3 players. If you love music like I do, purchasing thousands of songs only to lose them is entirely too much.   I think the Zune is easy to use, cool menu/navigation, easy to see the listings and was a really great buy, but *no* mp3 player is perfect. Obviously, the Marketplace and the WMP copycat software are kind of negatives, unless you don't use the software. Once again, I think the 14-hr battery-life claims with this player are a lie. I work 8 hours a day. I travel on the train to work for nearly an hour, and I travel home for nearly an hour. By the time I'm on the afternoon train, the battery is on its last leg, and there is usually 1-2 hours in that 10-hr time frame that I'm not even listening to the player. The album art...(sighs). That would be one of the coolest things to me if this weren't, once again, about pickiness with ID tags. Those of you who purchase songs from Zune's Marketplace might not have this issue. But if you're ripping songs from CD, downloading or other things, the ID tag information the Zune software picks up for many of your songs turns out incorrect. So you will sometimes either end up with the wrong album art for some songs, or you will end up with no album art. It's a pain in the @ss correcting the ID tags, particularly if you're wading through a lot of tracks. The battery charges up somewhat slowly with this player. It took next to no time for the Zen to charge, and you could listen to the Zen as it charged. With the Zune, it apparently takes knowing to close the Zune software in order to listen as it charges. Another issue with the ID tags--you can end up with several listings for the same song. For example, if in the ID tag info for the "album artist" is written differently from the song artist, it will create multiple listings for that song. It also does really weird grouping things, such as if more than one artist has the same album title those artists' album title will be grouped in under every other artist with that same title. So if you have "Greatest Hits" collections by several different artists on your player...all of their GH CDs will be listed under every artist with a GH CD on your player, as if Martina McBride is the artist of a Guns N Roses GH CD, for example. Crazy. Finally, the Zen and Zune have similar sound quality, except the Zen is louder. I realize some of you are like a walking, talking public announcement on hearing, but some songs you just want played really loud. I don't like that you can't correct tag issues and/or delete songs from your player without hooking the Zune back up to the computer and manually doing it from the Zune software. At least with the Zen, I could delete songs directly from the mp3 player and look at the ID tag information from the mp3 player (though I couldn't edit it from there).     My Biggest So-Whats: -The screen--I care next to nothing about being able to watch videos on an mp3 player. Wanna know why? Because I don't care how big or great-looking the screen/resolution is on an mp3 player, it's not going to be as big as, *at least*, a decent portable DVD player's screen...which still makes it--guess what--TOO SMALL to be interested in watching videos on one of those things. At least that's true for me. And if an mp3 player is big enough to see a video to my satisfaction, then that player is just too damn big. I'm sticking with my lap top and my TV on the video front. Besides, converting to WMV or any other format is a pain in the @ss and just not worth it, to me, and I don't care for how picky iPods and the Zune are about video formats. I'm sorry that I can't help those of you who care about that kind of thing in this review, but what I would say is if anything needing videos to be in WMV format and wanting the best picture quality are probably negatives for those who do care...although from what I've seen of the Zune's picture quality, it's pretty good.   -The weight--It's still not that big of a player, so I don't get the complaining about this. Most people I see with iPods have the ones that are not that much smaller than this Zune is.  -No scroll wheel--I had a touchpad on the Zen and was actually kind of annoyed with it sometimes. I have absolutely no problems with clicking a button, and I'm not sure why anyone else would have that problem, either.  -WiFi is "worthless"--True it is. The reason why, more than anything else, in my opinion, is that not many people have Zunes. I could really care less about the copyright/play/maintain restrictions on songs you send to others. You can easily go sit down and get the songs yourself, if you really want them. Indeed, that's how you've been getting along for the past few years anyways. But because of the fact that relatively few people have Zunes, you can turn on the WiFi feature anyway and not have anybody to send to/from nearby. I'm in Chicago right now, so as many people as I see all over the place--I've seen some with Zunes on the train--you'd think there'd be people on the WiFi feature...but that's just not the case.  -Not sold in other countries--I'm from the US, so...besides, it's a new player. -No engraving--No, but you can name your player from the Zune software, then go into "Settings" to see it. I don't really need either of those features. -Doesn't work with PlaysForSure--Good, because that was crap. I honestly think that was one of the problems with my Zen. This is one of the reasons why I say get your songs in universal formats and quit purchasing songs from picky player markets designed to keep you imprisoned to one mp3 player, because you ought to know that those are not always going to be compatible with other players, which means you're wasting money. If you must buy, buy from sites that will allow you to download in mp3 or wma format.  -Other things iPods have that the Zune doesn't--some people disregard the argument that Zunes are newer. But iPods really have been around for a long time. I don't see that many things missing with the Zune, though, that I would demand in an mp3 player, and most things I see listed by others are nitpicky not essentials. My biggest complaints as of right now are with the tagging issues/the fact that I can't have album art for every song without pulling teeth (which is not essential, so I can deal with it) and that the battery doesn't last as long as with the Zen nor charge fast enough. I think that if those are my biggest problems with the Zune, then the Zune is pretty alright. No problems with the buttons whatsoever, and my sister and brother have both said they haven't had any problems with their Zunes. Looking at the lists I recommended you see near the beginning of my story/review, I really don't see where the Zune is so much worse off than the iPod, as long as you're not picky and/or snobbish about looks/design.                       
<Overall>4

